Let me tell you something about my progression - it's not that I train every day like a mad man. It's that whenever I do train, I have a close connection with my body and I listen to it's needs.

Training is as much about making yourself feel happy, upbeat and pain-free as it about being strong, fit and confident.

It's the things we do when we don't have to that decide what we will be when we can't help it.

Whatever health and fitness goals you have, set the new year with good intentions. Routine is for robots. Feeling is for humans. This year, make a promise to do something every day - not to go to the gym even when you feel shit, not to push forward over that injury, but to respect and listen to your body more and do what it needs, not neccessarily what you want.

This may manifest itself as daily stretching, rehab, working out, more rest time, less rest time, etc. Give yourself what you need to become peaceful, joyful and strong. Focus on the inside, not the outside, and everything else will eventually begin to fall into place. "Nature does not hurry, yet everything is accomplished"

All training should be balanced, whichever aspect of your existence it focuses on. We must take care to cover all areas if we want to become the best we can be. For instance, many yogis are flexible, but not as strong as they want to be. Many athletes are strong, but not as mobile as they would like to be.

Now there are two main types of yoga practice which all different styles fall under, but we can extend that model to all types of training.

Yang type yoga/exercise is characterised by movements involving strength, control and energy in motion ('e'motion). Yin yoga/exercise is the opposite, focusing on flexibility, softness and mindfulness (detached state of consciousness). Of course, the perfect balance is mastery of both. By cultivating our skills on either side we can learn to balance our minds and bodies to perform at their peak.

Many people become excited when they think are learning to control their life force and energy - it can give an individual power in abundance. However many people gifted with the ability to tap into their Chi/Ki/Chakra/Prana do not purge themselves of the Yang element after utilising it. This leaves them tense, hard and stuck in GO mode. The other half of the spectrum is VITAL for optimum performance of the mind, body and spirit.

The aggression and resilience of the mind required to work your hardest and beat your personal best is YANG. The mental and physical release of effort and tension which aids recovery and long life is YIN. Neglect the other side of your preference at your own risk, because extremes based in duality will never defeat the whole.

Brazilian jiu-jitsu is a good example of lateral thinking coupled with physical prowess. Chess boxing and other games were played where the opponents would play chess intermittently between fighting rounds to challenge all aspects of themselves and each other.
This game also teaches the concept of spotlight consciousness and floodlight consciousness. Are you looking at part of the game, or the whole game? The ability to zoom in and out of what's going on around you is what keeps you in good perspective, grounded, and interacting with your environment in the most harmonious way possible. Interestingly, if you look at chess as if your opponent is yourself, you will much more appreciate the finer aspects of decision making in life - whether to advance, retreat, show mercy, surrender, sacrifice... if anything, i think the most important thing it's taught me is that you can spend a lifetime playing this game... but when it's over, regardless of who won, all the pieces go back in the box and become a chess set.

To push a skill to its limits, for instance a planche to planche push ups to maltese and onwards, is to take your understanding of that skill to the highest level. Once you understand many skills at a certain level, you begin to realise their connectedness and how they actually impact and assist or oppose other movements.

For instance a lot of planche training without handstand training makes your anterior delts tight and your vertical strength comparatively weaker than your horizontal strength. This means moving in between planche and handstand also becomes harder, as well as there being mobility issues if stretching discipline has not been applied.

In the opposite way, front lever training actually helps your planche training. Because the muscles involved in the horizontal stability are the same for both planche and front lever, but simply facing those forces in a different direction. Let's look at the lats for example. They are recruited in both exercises:
- in a front lever the lats pull the hands into the body
- in the planche the lats pull the body away from the hands.

Make sense?
The shoulder is different in the sense that a front lever is mainly posterior delt strength and a planche is anterior delt strength. And so on this day, Shiva sacrificed his own gain for the sake of all others, demonstrating pure Love despite his non-attachment and disdain for maya (this life of illusion). Is it harder for taller/larger people to do bodyweight exercises?

I've heard this debated alot, the usual response is that it's all relative to handling your own body with your own muscles so there is no difference.

After some research I found out that (purely mathematically) it's actually harder for a larger person. However I think genetics also does play a huge part in it all too (different starting muscle volume and contraction potential). DETAIL ▶️▶️ READ AND SHARE if you like understanding the finer aspects of biomechanics): Galileo's Square Cube Law states that "When an object undergoes a proportional increase in size, its new volume is proportional to the cube of the multiplier and its new surface area is proportional to the square of the multiplier." Basically put, If you double the size of a cube (measured by edge lengths), its surface area is increased by four times, but its volume is increased by eight times.

Muscle grows to it's natural size according to the surface area of the bones, it only develops extra volume and strength after training. The point of this law is that with living beings, if you double an organism's size assuming no training has been done, you end up with four times the muscle power moving eight times the mass, so instead of having the same relative agility as the original, the double-sized creature actually has only half.

This applies to flyers as well: Double the size, you get 4 times the wingpower attempting to keep 8 times the weight airborne, so the ability to fly has been cut by half. A full explanation for the biological aspect is more complicated due to subtler factors (muscle/bone stress, required oxygen uptake, dissipating body heat, etc.), the gist of it is the same in every case: You can't just scale something up (or down) to a different size and expect it to still work the same way as it used to.

Again, the law is not limited to living creatures, but applies to anything with mass including machinery and buildings. A skyscraper twice as wide and tall as another will have eight times the weight, and require a far stronger support structure — wood and brick just can't hold the weight.

Yesterday I watched Planetary, a documentary about our planet. I urge every one of you to watch it 🙌🏼🔝 Below are some of my notes.

You normally think of these images as an astronaut, in a spaceship, looking from outside of Earth, at the Earth. More fundamentally however, these images are the Earth looking at itself, through us. In other words, the first images from space are a critical moment in the emerging awakening of the Earth. Humans became planetary 40,000 years ago, but they didn't know that they existed on a planet. Through space travel we have become aware of home in a much larger context.

When looking at the Earth from space, we can finally get to a point where we are far enough away to not see our differences, right? Above the clouds you can see our vulnerable planet floating there, with a strong blue iridescence surrounding it which is the atmosphere which protects us and gave us life. You can then, for a moment, see us as just one species, as one population. We are a single species, but we are not singles.

There has to be a part of us that knows the Earth is in pain. That what brought us forth is in some sense dying. And our mainstream narrative allows us to feel numb and cuts us off from that inherent intuitive sense that something is really wrong in how we're relating to this only home of ours.

The belief that we have been created special. That we are above all other beings. It has lead us to become arrogant and think that we were the centre of the universe. But this is woefully wrong, because it stops us from seeing our connectedness with it, and in that we end up destroying it through our desecration of the Earth.

The world we now live in is less like the Earth we know and more like a curated museum. Where we are shown only what the curator wishes to put on display. Most of us live in cities where we hardly see any other living beings except a blade of grass in a crack on the pavement. But when you put a human into a natural setting, it's like giving water to a dry plant. Suddenly we go into our natural state, and we become aware again of the planet we are a part of and merge with it.

We are not ON the Earth. We are OF the Earth 🌍

MEAT EATING VERSUS VEGETARIANISM/VEGANISM

I have my own beliefs of right and wrong, as does everyone. But for a moment, let's put those aside and examine this from a logical perspective. I put this diagram together to share a couple of my thoughts on the matter.

1) If the purpose of eating is to GAIN energy, why would you choose to USE more energy in the process of getting it? Plants are more efficient food for energy absorption than meat.

2) If the other purpose of eating is to repair and build the body, why would you choose to spend energy and time breaking down a fully constructed and complex house (animal) into bricks, only to then build it all back into your own house (human)? Why not just get the simple bricks (vegetables) in the first place and start from there? And no, animal muscle does not convert directly into human muscle. It must be broken down into proteins and reconstructed into cells like everything else.

3) The more processes that something has done to it, the less of the original structure remains. The Sun is the source and giver of all life/energy on the planet. Why repackage that energy so many times to the point where it loses it's original vibration? We should absorb it as directly as possible - it's a shame we can't just absorb the Sun (raw energy) and be done with it, but because we are made of the Earth we need building blocks for our human form.

So then, why eat meat?
This is where the debate usually is.

Usually I hear the following reasons:
- Taste/craving (not a conscious decision, therefore not using any brain in the process)
- Meat has otherwise unobtainable proteins (not true)
- Difficulty of eating a varied enough plant based diet in the West where meat eating is rife (cultural and societal issue)
- Animals are below humans (no, they all feel pain and want to live as much as any other being. Try killing and eating someone's pet and see their reaction). I understand many may find this a strong viewpoint, and it is. And I'm not judging anyone for eating meat, each to their own. I'm just trying to share what I understand about the topic, because so many people ask me what my diet is like.

Thoughts welcome.

One thing which has really hit me since coming back from India is the change in my perspective.

From being immersed in a country where I was constantly surrounded by mountains, oceans, beaches, fields and deserts, it actually made my eyesight and field of vision change... I wasn't looking at screens, concrete and buildings anymore, I was looking at mud, grass, water and sand, stretching as far as the eye could see... Now I'm back in London and today I was riding my bike, but all of a sudden I realised I could see the whole road, the sky, rooftops and things I'd never noticed before, all in the same field of vision- it was like my eyes are seeing the place for the first time but from a broader, wider perspective... I've also found myself looking at my phone from further away than I used to, and my face feels more relaxed in general. Butterfly stroke (⏩x4) - Improves mobility and enhances spinal health (especially thoracic)
- Helps fix rounded shoulders when done slowly, consciously and correctly every day
- Useful prepatory exercise for any overhead movements

The point of this exercise is to strengthen the muscles around the scapulas and shoulder joints for overhead movements, without compensating through other muscles like the neck and lower back. The exercise also balances the muscles surrounding the joints and teaches the body healthy joint positioning.

It can be done more commonly holding a stick, however using a stick limits full expression on both sides.
The scapula (shoulder blade) should be retracted for most overhead movements so it should not ride up and forward during this exercise. Also the neck extensors should stay switched off throughout (shoulders pulled back and away from ears). The lower back must not be allowed to bend to compensate the feeling of gaining range - you must perform a controlled, articulated rotation through the shoulder joints for maximum benefits.

Tass has a developing scoliosis (side bending) of the spine and also symptoms of sciatica (pinched nerve into the leg)... but it is still in the early phases and as such these can be caught by screening movement patterns followed by a rehabilitation programme. Obviously it's not ideal to have blockages or pain and so it's of utmost importance to be body aware and make sure you're taking care of any niggles, aches, misalignment and so forth (both passive positions and during movement). In scoliosis, the musculature on one side of the spine is stronger and tighter than the other - this pulls the discs of the spine to one side and sets off a wave of dysfunction up and down the spine which soon finds its way into your limbs and movement patterns.

You can see from the second picture how different Tass's seated side bends are, with the deeper curve to the right due to less support from the muscles and compensation into the lower back/shoulder.

Finally is to then feel and connect with the entire energy grid of consciousness - and in that space there is such a hoard of treasures for well being and peace of mind, we should never forget it. Free and accessible at all times, it is that realm and state of being that holds the secrets to all achievements and success.

*SWISS BALL PLANK TO PIKE LIFT* - Develops spinal control, shoulder, wrist and hip mobility
- Engages deep abdominal wall and thus enhances ability to pike as well as
draw the legs through the arms from L-sit
- Massively helpful training progression for hand balancing

STEPS:
1. Begin in a plank with your hands shoulder width apart and your knees on the swiss ball

2. Pull your hips into the sky whilst simultaneously extending the shoulders above head

3. As the feet draw in nearer to the body on the way up, pull the ball into you with your feet, using your hips and abs to fold the body

4. Ensure in the final position that elbows, knees and spine are all straight and tight.

Tip: Keep the movement as slow and controlled as possible - moving quickly or throwing the body up with no control reduces stability and offers far less gains.
